body:
@TheRook I'm not sure I'm following what you're saying. The original issue is about custom errors but you are then talking about `.to.emit`, which is related to events?

Anyway, re-reading the original issue, I see at least one problem:

```
.to.be.revertedWith('InvalidSignature("0xfc39486c750a6cd425dc41cc85f043e3fe29634868b5be6a5ad2e22c470e21b1")');
```

That's not the way to assert that a custom error was thrown. `.revertedWith` is for reverts with reason strings (that is, things like `require(false, "my error string")`). That's why the error message is telling you that it was expecting it to revert with a given reason string, but that it reverted with a custom error instead.

As explained [in the docs](https://hardhat.org/hardhat-chai-matchers/docs/reference#.revertedwithcustomerror), you have to use `.to.be.revertedWithCustomError` for custom errors.

With respect to the line numbers, I created this contract:

```solidity
contract Foo {
  error MyCustomError(uint code);
  error MyOtherCustomError(uint code);

  function f() public {
    revert MyCustomError(123);
  }
}
```

and wrote this test:

```js
describe("Foo", function () {
  it("Should revert with custom error", async function () {
    const Foo = await ethers.getContractFactory("Foo");
    const foo = await Foo.deploy();

    await expect(foo.f()).to.be.revertedWithCustomError(
      foo,
      "MyCustomError"
    ).withArgs(123)
  });
});
```

The test passes correctly. If I change it to `.revertedWith("MyCustomError(123)")`, which is similar to what you were doing, the test (correctly) fails, and I get the line number of the test. Again, in previous versions the line numbers were not working, but in the latest version they should work. You can update with `npm i @nomicfoundation/hardhat-chai-matchers@latest`

I did uncover a couple of problems while looking into this. One is that when we say "with a custom error" we should include the selector of the custom error, because that could be useful. The other one is that we are not handling rejected promises correctly in some scenarios, but that it's unrelated to your problem. I'm going to create separate issues for those.

@fvictorio  The lack of line numbers is 1/2 of this, the other 1/2 is that you aren't reporting what event was emitted.  The final event in the log will be a success event, if you are expecting a failure then the engineer should know what the mistmatch is - it should say "XXX Event was emitted instead" or "No event emitted".

Also Jesus Christ, words cannot express how much time we have wasted trying to fix tests that don't have line numbers.  Idk what kind of projects you use this for - but we are pushing over 400 tests and its literally impossible to find out what is filling without adding print statements :(

These error messages are so bad, I dread using your software. I'm sorry but telling me you don't need to list the event mistmatch doesn't make me feel any better about hardhat.
